1. Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) in R

Why Use OOP in R?

	•	Encapsulates data and methods in objects, improving reusability and maintainability.
	•	Simplifies the management of complex data structures and processes.
	•	Facilitates the design of scalable pipelines.

Key OOP Systems in R

	1.	S3 System:
	•	Flexible and widely used.
	2.	R6 System:
	•	True object-oriented system with encapsulation and inheritance.
	3.	S4 System:
	•	Rigorous and formal, used in advanced applications.

Practical Example: R6 for a Preprocessing Pipeline

Current Workflow Without OOP:

clean_data <- function(data) {
  data <- data %>%
    filter(!is.na(target)) %>%
    mutate(across(where(is.character), as.factor))
  return(data)
}

preprocess_data <- function(data) {
  data <- clean_data(data)
  data <- scale(select(data, where(is.numeric)))
  return(data)
}

Refactored Workflow with R6:

library(R6)

# Define Preprocessor Class
Preprocessor <- R6Class(
  "Preprocessor",
  public = list(
    data = NULL,
    initialize = function(data) {
      self$data <- data
    },
    clean_data = function() {
      self$data <- self$data %>%
        filter(!is.na(target)) %>%
        mutate(across(where(is.character), as.factor))
      invisible(self)
    },
    scale_numeric = function() {
      self$data <- self$data %>%
        mutate(across(where(is.numeric), scale))
      invisible(self)
    },
    get_data = function() {
      return(self$data)
    }
  )
)

# Usage Example
data <- read.csv("data/raw_data.csv")
preprocessor <- Preprocessor$new(data)
processed_data <- preprocessor$clean_data()$scale_numeric()$get_data()

Benefits:

	•	Encapsulation: Encapsulates all preprocessing logic within the Preprocessor class.
	•	Chaining: Allows method chaining for cleaner code.
	•	Reusability: Can be extended for different preprocessing pipelines.

2. Next-Level Modularity Practices

Why Improve Modularity?

	•	Makes code more reusable and easier to debug.
	•	Improves flexibility by making functions more parametric.
	•	Simplifies testing and scaling.

Common Issues in Existing Modularity

	1.	Functions have hardcoded parameters.
	2.	Functions are not designed for generalization.
	3.	High coupling between modules.

Improvement Example: Flexible Functions

Before: Hardcoded Parameters

split_data <- function(data) {
  train <- data[1:floor(0.7 * nrow(data)), ]
  test <- data[(floor(0.7 * nrow(data)) + 1):nrow(data), ]
  return(list(train = train, test = test))
}

After: Parametric and Flexible

split_data <- function(data, train_size = 0.7, seed = NULL) {
  if (!is.null(seed)) set.seed(seed)
  train_index <- sample(1:nrow(data), size = floor(train_size * nrow(data)))
  train <- data[train_index, ]
  test <- data[-train_index, ]
  return(list(train = train, test = test))
}

# Example Usage
data <- iris
splits <- split_data(data, train_size = 0.8, seed = 42)

Improvement Example: Grouping Related Functions

Before: Scattered Functions

compute_mean <- function(data, column) {
  mean(data[[column]], na.rm = TRUE)
}

compute_sd <- function(data, column) {
  sd(data[[column]], na.rm = TRUE)
}

After: Group Functions in a List or Package

stats_functions <- list(
  mean = function(data, column) {
    mean(data[[column]], na.rm = TRUE)
  },
  sd = function(data, column) {
    sd(data[[column]], na.rm = TRUE)
  }
)

# Example Usage
mean_value <- stats_functions$mean(iris, "Sepal.Length")
sd_value <- stats_functions$sd(iris, "Sepal.Length")

3. Using a config.yaml File

Why Use a config.yaml File?

	•	Centralizes project settings and parameters.
	•	Simplifies environment management.
	•	Avoids hardcoding, making the project more scalable.

Practical Example: Refactor with config.yaml

Step 1: Create config.yaml

default: &default
  data:
    raw_path: "data/raw_data.csv"
    processed_path: "data/processed_data.csv"
  model:
    type: "xgboost"
    parameters:
      nrounds: 100
      max_depth: 6
      eta: 0.1

development:
  <<: *default
  model:
    parameters:
      nrounds: 50  # Reduced for quick testing

production:
  <<: *default
  model:
    parameters:
      nrounds: 200

Step 2: Load Configuration

library(yaml)

load_config <- function(env = "default") {
  config <- yaml::read_yaml("config.yaml")
  return(config[[env]])
}

# Load Production Config
config <- load_config("production")
print(config)

Step 3: Refactor Code

# Use Config Settings
data <- read.csv(config$data$raw_path)

# Train XGBoost Model
library(xgboost)
model <- xgboost(
  data = as.matrix(data),
  nrounds = config$model$parameters$nrounds,
  max_depth = config$model$parameters$max_depth,
  eta = config$model$parameters$eta,
  objective = "binary:logistic"
)

4. Implementation Plan

	1.	Object-Oriented Refactoring:
